    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2103946130" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2103946130" />
    <a title="Jeanette" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11869072-jeanette"><img alt="Jeanette" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1372095557p2/11869072.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2103946130?book_show_action=true">Nov 17, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jeanette" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jeanette" href="/user/show/11869072-jeanette">Jeanette</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780316225908" href="/book/show/34379864-two-kinds-of-truth">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2103946130" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17548934089848150864">Because of the excellent writing, the intricate entwining cases, and most especially the grit of Harry Bosch exposed during this assault on his character and honest methods- this probably and for most would earn a 5 star ratings. My lack was felt (by 1/2 a star only so I would make it fully 4.5 star)in the depth of the procedural information. It was sure slow going for me during the meet and greets and transport to intersect and introductory leg work and &quot;get the right guy or hire a dick for tha</span>
  <span id="freeText17548934089848150864" style="display:none">Because of the excellent writing, the intricate entwining cases, and most especially the grit of Harry Bosch exposed during this assault on his character and honest methods- this probably and for most would earn a 5 star ratings. My lack was felt (by 1/2 a star only so I would make it fully 4.5 star)in the depth of the procedural information. It was sure slow going for me during the meet and greets and transport to intersect and introductory leg work and "get the right guy or hire a dick for that aspect" to talk to time and again. From pages about 70 to almost 200, it was a constantly moving map location puzzle with 2 ex-partners and all kinds of Haller associates fixed as moving targets in the mix. Not a complaint at all, but only to note that just "for me" it was approaching a Mickey Haller more than a Harry Bosch within those long periods for "set up". Because this really is 2 books and 3 cases. And yet, and yet- it is NOT switching time frames or eras or placements or narrators. Not at all. <br /><br />Because Michael Connelly is genius at what he does. He gets them all in real time. Exactly like a copper and most on the street police "get it" themselves. So just as in real life, when the crisis goes down in one set, there is apt to be void for the absolutely needed input in another. LOVE, LOVE that. He also did it in his new series with Renee, Late Show. <br /><br />Other than a debut author or two, and I believe one of them was English- the writers who get the overlaps of real time police work are mightily scarce as the old cliche of "hen's teeth".<br /><br />There was a spell of frenetic tension here where Harry goes undercover for a short period. It was crazy well plotted. Could I see a movie version of that scenario!<br /><br />But no plot tells. And no Maddy or Mickey info that you don't want to hear. Suffice it to add that they are both in the mix and Mickey to such an extent that this could be labeled as a Bosch/Haller for both series. But the doing the titling with #22 AND #29 is accurate. Two HUGE and intense active cases that are actually enough for a book each. And then another cold case, which we KNOW is Harry's bread and butter at this point as he is NOT LAPD but is working for San Fernando instead on more of piecework basis. But now his LAPD historic reputation for convictions and core integrity record for those decades of years is clearly at stake too. Police as a target! Could it get more timely? Yes it can because it's opioids cartel in the other scenario. <br /><br />Love, love my over 65 Bosch, btw. I don't think he is at all such as disparity for his age. And not all 70 year olds are tottering physical wrecks with mental lapses either. Just saying. But you'd never know that by the books published in this decade.<br /><br />There's just a bit too much lawyer talk and supposition in here for me, but it was a very exciting and attention keeping read. All hail, Michael Connelly! He begins a point where the real world and fiction actually sometimes meet. And does it quite artfully too.<br /><br />Lastly, the ending is awesome. And the most equivocal to life's presumptions! Because sometimes fallen and forgotten victims, are not what they have seemed. And beyond that there is the case coming up which is going to be pivotal to a promise.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17548934089848150864" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

